e}\" data-wp-block-name=\"core/paragraph\"\u003eMany dealerships either weren’t familiar with the reporting process or simply missed the deadline, leaving EV buyers frustrated. Even worse, some dealers fronted the credit to customers expecting to be reimbursed by the IRS, only to find themselves out of pocket when they failed to meet the reporting requirement.\u003c/p\u003e\n            \n        \n            \n        \n            \n        \n            \n        \n\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"a-long-awaited-fix\"\u003eA long-awaited fix\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\n\u003cp data-wp-block=\"{\u0026#34;dropCap\u0026#34;:false}\" data-wp-block-name=\"core/paragraph\"\u003eThanks in part to pressure from the National Automobile Dealers Association (NADA), the IRS has now lifted the strict three-day deadline, allowing dealers to retroactively report sales for any qualifying EV purchased in 2024. The change is already in effect, and dealers can start using the updated IRS portal immediately.\u003c/p\u003e\n            \n        \n            \n        \n\n\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"2025 Ford Mustang Mach-E\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"5652\" height=\"3286\" decoding=\"async\" data-nimg=\"1\" sizes=\"(min-width: 750px) 750px, calc(100vw - 60px)\" srcset=\"https://www.autoblog.com/.image/w_16,q_auto:good,c_limit/MjEyNTY2MTA5MzY1MzQ3ODQ5/2025-ford-mustang-mach-e-8.jpg 16w, https://www.autoblog.com/.image/w_32,q_auto:good,c_limit/MjEyNTY2MTA5MzY1MzQ3ODQ5/2025-ford-mustang-mach-e-8.jpg 32w, https://www.autoblog.com/.image/w_48,q_auto:good,c_limit/MjEyNTY2MTA5MzY1MzQ3ODQ5/2025-ford-mustang-mach-e-8.jpg 48w, https://www.autoblog.com/.image/w_64,q_auto:good,c_limit/MjEyNTY2MTA5MzY1MzQ3ODQ5/2025-ford-mustang-mach-e-8.jpg 64w, https://www.autoblog.com/.image/w_96,q_auto:good,c_limit/MjEyNTY2MTA5MzY1MzQ3ODQ5/2025-ford-mustang-mach-e-8.jpg 96w, https://www.autoblog.com/.image/w_128,q_auto:good,c_limit/MjEyNTY2MTA5MzY1MzQ3ODQ5/2025-ford-mustang-mach-e-8.jpg 128w, https://www.autoblog.com/.imag